<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-291-662  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 291 662.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>ESD: The Electronic System Design Magazine  May 1989 v19 n5p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>RISC finds a home on VME graphics units. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilson, A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The advent of Reduced Instruction-Set Computing (RISC) and othernew technologies are changing development strategies for bothworkstation and board-level vendors engaged in building graphicsworkstations around the VMEbus.andP;  Workstation vendors are nowsupplying their own host CPU's.andP;  Sun Microsystems Inc hasannounced the 3-470 GX, 3-470 GXP, and 3-470-TAAC graphicsworkstations, all of which use its own CPU design based on the68030 processor.andP;  Board-level vendors are concentrating onimproving graphics capabilities while taking advantage of existingCPU's.andP;  Omnicomp's new 8800 graphics board combine the latest VLSIimprovements from Texas Instruments and Motorola with a PAL-NTSCframe grabber.andP;  Adage Inc is using RISC on its graphics engine.andO;Neither vendor has developed its own CPU.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Sun Microsystems Inc. (product development).andO;Product:   Sun Microsystems Sun-3-470GX (Workstation)Sun Microsystems Sun-3-470GXP (Workstation).andO;Topic:     Reduced-Instruction-Set ComputersVMEbusComputer GraphicsMemory Boards-CardsCPUCustomization.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>